@Jesse 

😀

The next time I do something that makes my wife mad, I'm going to call her a pair of overalls.

@Helen Wright 
Does it help to remember ATHENS is in Greece, so that ATHENA....would be Greek?


Though she did ROAM around a lot.

@Warren 

While I loved this Strands, and was able to finish it quickly, I couldn't help wondering about younger players: do they know it as well as older players do? Today's students have to learn more history, how to hide in a closet, what to do in an emergency, how to apply a tourniquet properly, and this century's version of New Math. (Remember Whole Language? That was the 80s.) They may not learn cursive, or what happened along the Tigris and Euphrates, or the three branches of government, and checks and balances. So... great lit? I just wonder... 

But I bet they do way better than I do on Sports Connections, which I gave up on almost immediately.

@Eric Hougland 

Yeah, my first thought was to look for the double letters in “bells,” “Annabel,” “Annie,” etc.

I was thinking it would be neat if they picked a poet or author and had us look for titles, although just focusing on “The Raven” worked here.

@Rosalind Mitchell 

It's more of a light-hearted version of anyhow. It's meant to be cutesy, when using "anyhow" can sound dismissive.

I use it a lot in speech and text (casual conversation) but would not use it in formal writing.

@Rosalind Mitchell - “Anyhow,…” is what you say when you want to return to the main subject at hand.
“Anyhoo…” is what you say when what you mean is that the other person is an idiot who is speaking off-topic.

They are both very useful words, and entirely distinct.

@Mr Dave 

I was surprised to read that “The first known use of anyhoo was in 1850.” 

Woah!

@Mr Davey 

They do Thanksgiving in October in Canada, because by the time November rolls around it's too cold for them to be thankful for much of anything.

I jest.  I love the cold, and would love to spend the rest of my Thanksgivings in Canada.

@Francis 

I expect Natdegu was unable to decide between AMEND and eMEND for 11D, given their understandable unfamiliarity with DACA. 

I don’t much care for the federal government’s predilection for acronyms and had DoCA before I remembered the “Action.”

@Eric Hougland 

Oh, I see, DACA was the cross.

Perfect example of how little I actually cogitate on my answers.  I'm sure I filled in DACA and never even noticed the clue.

